{[%evp 0,15,7,-4,-4,-12,-5,-19,-19,-19,-23,-23,-23,-25,-22,-24,-17,-17] This is the first position I would like to discuss with you. After our move (5.Nc3), Black has three options, and as I said, all of them look exactly the same. The first and most obvious option is d6. So, first of all, we should understand why this move is not considered to be precise.} 6. Na4 $1 {In one of his books, Dvoretsky teaches us about the "Principle of the drawback." The idea behind this concept is that all moves in chess have some kind of drawback. You will see exactly that in our survey. What is the drawback of the move d6? Let me explain: it takes control of some squares from the c5-bishop. How can we exploit this factor? Exactly, with Na4! This not only threatens to take the bishop, but thanks to the pawn on d6, the bishop no longer has the e7 square available. For this reason, it is only after d6 that we can go for Na4! Never forget that. After this move, Black only has one adequate response, which is:} Bb6 {In our theoretical coverage, we will see exactly why the move a3 is much more precise than c3 in this position. But at this moment, I just want to explain why this kind of structure is good for us.} 7. a3 (7. O-O O-O 8. a3) 7... O-O 8. O-O Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 {This is the structure I would like to discuss with you. In the theoretical part, you will understand exactly how to proceed in these lines, but it is important to understand the nature of the advantage for White in such a scenario and why this is good for us. The basic response to this question is that our pawn structure is much better, for the simple reason that Black has these doubled pawns on e6-e5 and potentially (after Nxb6) also doubled pawns on b6-b7. You may ask: "But why is this a weakness at all if it is impossible to attack these pawns?" And you are right. So what is the point of this position?  It is the following: The thing about these doubled pawns is not that we can press or attack them. It is just that Black's structure in itself is not mobile. It is much harder to advance these kinds of doubled pawns. The fact that Black has these two doubled pawns (b6+b7, and after Be6 fxe6, another one) turns Black's position very passive, for the simple reason that it is almost impossible to mobilize these pawns. In the meantime, White has a perfect pawn structure and can slowly prepare the advance of their pawns: b4-c4-c5, or even prepare the d4 break. In the meantime, thanks to their passive structure, Black is doomed to passive defense, and for this reason, this kind of position is considered to be very passive for Black. In the theoretical coverage, I will show you that this position is much worse than it looks.} 10. c3 $1 Ne7 11. b4 $14 {Black is just much worse here. In the theoretical section, you will find more details.} *

