{[%evp 0,5,19,21,21,21,31,-38] [#]} 5. Nc3 {And here, dear reader, I think you can start to understand why strong players are a little scared of this d6 move. After this explanation, we can start to understand the popularity of the move.} a6 $5 {The reasoning behind that is very simple: if Na4 is such a problem, then Black goes for ...a7-a6 first (safeguarding the a7-square for the bishop) and only after that go for ...d7-d6. But the move ...a7-a6 also has a deep drawback. First of all, this move loses a full tempo. But the question is: how to exploit this? In practice, White players are trying to prove that the way to exploit the a6 move is to go for Be3. After ...Bxe3 fxe3, a position arises that puts the following question: what is this pawn doing on a6? Think about that for a second: the advance ...a7-a6 is very useful to free the a7-square for the bishop, but if in the following move you exchange your c5-bishop, then you just lose a full tempo! This is fair enough, and I think this move is playable. But when preparing this line, I found a new concept that I would like to introduce to you right now.} 6. Bg5 {This move itself is not new. But after} h6 {White will play} 7. Bh4 $5 {The point! This move is considered to be bad in all the sources that I found about this position. However, after analyzing it more deeply, I found that this is completely wrong, and the move is totally playable. This is a very interesting thing because not only are the positions arising from it interesting, but we are also going to surprise our opponents when we play it. I will explain all the details of this position in our theoretical coverage. If the positions are too sharp for your taste, don't worry! Be3 is also a totally playable move, and you can vary between the two without any problems. But for this survey, I will focus our analysis on the Bg5-Bh4 idea.} (7. Bxf6 {is what theory suggests, but I dislike the resulting positions. Black is just ok here.}) *

