{[%evp 0,5,21,17,25,17,37,43] [#]} 5. Nc3 {If you have been following our thought process in the first parts of this course, a question that finally arises is: "OK, now I see. So Black goes for ...h7-h6! In this way, we avoid Na4 (the pawn is still on d7, so after Na4, Black has the Be7 response, and the knight is doing nothing on a4, forget that!) And also, different from a6, there's no Bg5 anymore. So let's see!} h6 $5 {But here, dear reader, it turns out that ...h7-h6 also has its drawbacks! Of course, it has the advantage of cutting off the Bg5 option. But talking about the drawbacks, first of all, it also loses a full tempo. But much more than that, it loses two! Because if Black wants to avoid the Na4 option by White, soon they will be forced to lose another tempo with ...a7-a6 to safeguard their bishop. After so many lost tempos by Black, we can finally go for the Be3 structure, with the argument that the pawns on h6 and a6 are just not that useful after all. Moreover, in certain scenarios, it is also reasonable to argue that the pawn is better placed on h7 than h6 because the pawn on h6 weakens the kingside a bit, and it can cause some trouble for Black in the future. In the theoretical part, I will explain exactly the move orders for you and why you should avoid Be3 for now. But for the moment, I just want to say that in my opinion, the most precise move is:} 6. h3 a6 {AND ONLY AFTER this advance, you go for Be3.} 7. Be3 $1 {In my opinion, White can fight for an advantage here.} *

