{[%evp 0,29,40,39,25,12,8,28,7,6,12,5,12,-4,2,-12,-12,-19,-9,-20,-20,-17,-19,-20,-16,-17,-14,-23,4,-24,-19,-22]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 {As I explained in our "model sections" part, this very natural move is considered to be imprecise due to:} (5... O-O {As explained in the "Model sections," this move has no independent value, and after 0-0, it just transposes to all the places and lines already analyzed in this course.} 6. O-O h6 (6... a6 7. Bg5) (6... d6 {All these moves transpose to Chapter 1, 2, and 3 respectively.} 7. Na4) 7. h3 a6 (7... d6 8. Na4) 8. Be3) 6. Na4 $1 Bb6 7. a3 $3 {I understand that it looks strange to put two exclamation marks to such a normal move. But the point of this move is VERY deep. And the second exclamation mark is more subjective: I love this move. The first time I saw it, I immediately started to ask myself: Why is this move better than c3? After all, c3 is a move that we are going to need anyway, and after Nxb6 axb6, it is probable that we will need this a2 pawn on a4, not on a3. So why waste time with a3? Let's check.} (7. O-O O-O 8. Nxb6 axb6 9. a3 {leads to very similar positions, but I recommend that you delay the Nxb6 option as much as possible because in certain cases, we have additional plans apart from Nxb6 (line a3-b4-c4).}) (7. c3 O-O 8. O-O {If now Black goes for} h6 ({In case of} 8... Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Nxb6 axb6 11. a4 {We are really in a better version of the line. White is just better here. The reasons are explained in the "Model examples" part, and I recommend that you read the things we discussed there. This is a better version because here we manage to play a2-a4 in one go, instead of a2-a3 and a3-a4 in two steps, as in our main line.}) 9. h3 {But dear reader, please pay attention to this moment because it is here that we understand "why" this c3 move is not precise:} Ne7 $3 {I understand, it looks totally normal. But the thing is that this exact plan (with Ne7) DOES NOT WORK against our a3 line! Let's continue a bit to understand what the difference is.} 10. Nxb6 axb6 11. Re1 Ng6 {And here, a move that White would love to play to activate his bishop is} 12. d4 {But after} exd4 {White has no good way to mantain the center. Lets check:} 13. Qxd4 {Please pay attention to this position. After Re8, White has a problem: the bishop on c1 has no future. But just imagine for a second that this pawn on c3 was instead on c2. If that was the case, White would have the very strong positional move b2-b3. Then, the bishop would find its future on b2. But with the pawn on c3, the diagonal is closed for this bishop, and for this reason, White has no advantage here.} (13. Nxd4 Nxe4 $1 14. Rxe4 d5) (13. cxd4 Nxe4 $1 14. Rxe4 d5 $11) 13... Re8 $11 {In my opinion, Black is even slightly better here. The incredible thing is that with the pawn on a3 (instead of c3), White is just better! Check the lines below to understand.}) 7... O-O 8. O-O {You can always play Nxb6, but the thing is that this bishop is not going anywhere for now. Therefore, it is useful to maintain the tension. I would like to examine three plans: Be6 directly (main line), Ne7-g6, and the more solid Re8+Be6.} h6 (8... Ne7 {Lets start from this move in order to understand why Black prefers the inclusion of the moves h2-h3 and ...h7-h6.} 9. Nxb6 axb6 10. Bg5 $1 {For this reason, it is better to include the moves ...h7-h6 and h2-h3 before going for the Ne7 plan.} Ng6 11. Nh4 $1 $14) 9. h3 Be6 (9... Re8 10. Re1 Be6 11. Bxe6 Rxe6 {And here, we understand why we delayed Nxb6. Because here we can go for} 12. b4 $1 (12. Nxb6 {is also possible, but it is more flexible to start with b4.} axb6 13. c4 {In my opinion, this position is very pleasant for White as well.}) 12... Ne7 13. c4 {And apart from the obvious Nxb6, we also start to speculate with c4-c5. But after} c6 {we can finally go for} 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. Bb2 {Planning to proceed with Qc2 and d3-d4. We can also consider expanding on the queenside by means of a3-a4.}) (9... Ne7 {This is a better way to implement the idea of Ne7, but it still doesn't work so well.} 10. Nxb6 {I see no big reasons to avoid this move anymore.} axb6 11. Re1 Ng6 {but here comes a crucial point of our line -} 12. d4 (12. b4 {is possible, but not so precise.}) 12... exd4 13. Qxd4 Re8 14. b3 $3 $14 {This is the main idea behind the a3 move order. Now that the pawn on c3 is no longer blocking the a1-h8 diagonal, the bishop can be easily activated and become a powerful piece.} Be6 15. Bb2 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 {With such strong bishop on b2, a natural way to try to restrict White´s activity is:} Ne5 {But after} 17. Qc3 $14 {Black is in a very passive position due to the pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal. White is just much better here.} (17. Nxe5 {is possible as well.} dxe5 18. a4 {Fixing the doubled pawns. White is also better here. Even though White is better here, I prefer maintaining the tension.})) 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. c3 {It is possible to play simpler with Nxb6 followed by Be3, as explained in the model section. But White can hope for even more here. Our plan includes b4+c4, followed by Nxb6 and preparation for d4. This is a very general way of describing White's ideas, so caution is advised. Our strategy depends on what Black does in the meantime.} Ne7 {This is the most obvious plan.} (11... Qe8 {This is another way to handle Black's position. Black is attempting to activate his queen as quickly as possible, but this plan also has some drawbacks: Black's knight on c6 remains out of play. This is a common theme in the Italian, where the knight on c6 is frequently misplaced, and various Ne7-g6 maneuvers are attempted. However, for the moment, we will continue to follow our main plan.} 12. b4 {Remember: If the bishop on b6 is not threatening to move, you can delay the capture on b6 and keep playing all the useful moves you can. In this way, 1- You maintain the tension a little longer and keep your opponents guessing "when" you are going to take. But the most important thing is 2- You also keep a second plan in hand, the c4-c5 threat. Of course, it is always possible to take the bishop on b6 and follow with a3-a4 and Be3. This position is generally comfortable for White. I just think we can fight for even more!} Nh5 {Looks like the most consistent option for Black. He continues to avoid the move Ne7. Now, I would like to introduce an idea that is typical for these positions and is essential to know:} 13. Ra2 $3 {I'm sorry for using so many exclamation marks here; maybe I went too far. But let me explain: the exclamation marks are for the beauty of this maneuver. The first time I saw this rook lift in similar positions, I immediately fell in love with it. What's the idea behind it? First of all, this rook helps to protect our pawn on f2, which is useful considering the pressure on the f-file. Secondly, if in the near future we go for the advance c3-c4, Bd4 will not be a tempo against our rook. But in general, the first point is more important: your rook is just better placed here} Nf4 {The most consistent move. And now I suggest the simple and strong} 14. Bxf4 Rxf4 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. a4 {You may ask, "Why are we trading all these pieces?" The point here is that we are trading a lot of pieces, but the most important one for Black (the worst one) is still on the board - the c6-knight. If we are trading pieces, but this bad knight is still in the game, then things are going well for us. Of course, there remains the question: What if Black tries to activate this piece now? Let's see.} Ne7 {And now, I would like to show you a way to neutralize Black's activity once and for all!} 17. Nh2 $1 {Remember this idea! The knight on h2 is very solidly placed. It may look bad, but it covers a lot of important squares around our king. And without the knight on f3, there's no pressure on the f-file anymore. After that, you are free to start your central action and prepare d3-d4.} Ng6 18. Re1 Qf7 19. g3 Rf6 20. Re3 {We are threatening Ng4.} (20. Ng4 Rf3) 20... Qd7 21. Kg2 $14 {And Black is having a terrible time, He is just MUCH worse and very passive here. There´s no counterplay anywhere, His pressure on the f-file was totally neutralized, Our king is perfectly safe now.}) 12. b4 Ng6 13. c4 Nd7 (13... c6 {And here we arrive at a moment where I think White can use the fact that he mantained the tension a little longer, and instead of the more normal (and strong Nxb6) we can also go for} 14. c5 $1 dxc5 15. Nxc5 $14 {Black is in a horrible shape.}) 14. Nxb6 axb6 15. Be3 $14 {White is ready to expand on the kingside by means of a3-a4. Black does not have any counterplay.} *

