{[%evp 0,37,19,36,28,10,18,18,18,18,7,18,20,8,26,6,13,13,-15,-29,-29,-29,-7,-25,-23,-32,-1,-26,-26,-33,10,18,18,-15,26,17,17,28,13,13]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 $5 {And now, dear reader, I would like to suggest two different lines. The first one (and our main recommendation) is 6.Bg5. This move was my main recommendation. But for those who hope to play in a more thematic way (similar plans as in the h6 lines), I will also suggest a totally different approach in my "Bonus Repertoire" that you can check at the end of the database. I suggest you include both options in your repertoire! After all, the Italian is all about being flexible, and it never hurts to have two different options. But for now, I would like to analyze with you a totally new concept that I analyzed when preparing for the recent Tata Steel Group B Tournament.} 6. Bg5 (6. a4 $5 {This is my second recommentation, and I analyse it in the ''Bonus Chapters''. It is also very interesting.}) 6... h6 7. Bh4 $5 {This move is relatively new, not in the sense that it has never been played before, but rather in the sense that it is considered to be bad by most sources covering this line. However, I hope this survey will help change this assessment.} (7. Bxf6 {This is a very safe way to play the position, and if you're looking for a risk-free position, this is undoubtedly a good option. But at the same time, this line is not challenging for Black, and Black can just equalize after a series of precise moves that strong players tend to know. For this reason, my suggestion is 7.Bh4. However, for the sake of completeness, I will show some ideas in this Bxf6 line too, and then you can conclude for yourself how likely it is that your opponents will find the moves.} Qxf6 8. Nd5 Qd8 9. c3 d6 10. d4 exd4 (10... Ba7 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Qh5 {At first, this looks SUPER dangerous. In my opinion, against non-prepared opponents, it is dangerous. Unfortunately, Black has an adequate response here.} O-O $1 14. Qxe5 Re8 15. Qf4 Qd6 $1 {Only move. But after that, I found nothing better for White than} 16. Qxd6 Rxe4+ 17. Ne3 cxd6 18. Bd5 Re7 19. O-O-O {And here, after} Be6 {Black is just equal. The bishop on a7 is too strong for White to be better. But as you can see, there's no risk involved in this line, and White is just solid and fine. However, I found the problems arising after 7.Bh4 (instead of Bxf6) to be more serious and important. In the 7.Bh4 line, Black's problems are yet to be solved.} ({A mistake would be} 19... Bxe3+ {when after} 20. fxe3 Rxe3 21. Rhf1 {Black is worse.})) 11. cxd4 Ba7 12. h3 {Looks totally playable for me.}) 7... Be7 {The main move 7...g5 will be dealt with in the next chapter.  Now I would like to explain a few things about such positions. For this, we should try to understand the nature of having the bishop on e7 instead of c5. When the bishop is on e7, it is more passive. Thus, you don't need to be afraid of moves like g5 anymore because the passivity of the bishop does not combine with violent measures anymore. On the other hand, the bishop on e7 kills the pin without the need for such drastic moves as g5. This means that Black's position is not so exposed anymore. In other words, you should understand that the nature of the position is much more calm. You should forget aggressive options for now and focus on playing strong positional moves.  Black's intentions in such positions are to try to take one of the white bishops. So keep alert to both Na5 and Nh5 options (with Na5 being the more urgent for now). After solving this more urgent issue, you can claim a slight edge because of your space advantage. The structure is very similar, but your c4 bishop is much more active and strong than its e7 counterpart.} (7... d6 $5 {On one hand, this move can be a little bit annoying, but on the other hand, it is difficult to play in practice. I understand that d6 looks like a totally normal move, but in reality, you can't play it without calculating the proper consequences of 8.Nd5, and this is far from easy! But first, let me clarify what I mean by "annoying". The thing here is that Black can play g5 on the next move, and in this move order, he cuts off certain options for White. But as I said, he also gives us additional options! So, in general, don't worry too much about this. But having said that, let's check some ways to deal with this move.} 8. Nd5 {As I mentioned earlier, playing ...d7-d6 without considering the consequences of 8.Nd5 would be unwise, and I believe that just the possibility of this move is enough to dissuade Black from entering this position. It is not at all practical to calculate this line in a practical game, especially when 7...g5 is a perfectly reasonable and normal move to play.} (8. a3 $5 {is playable as well.}) (8. Nd2 {This move is an attempt to reach a similar position as in the main line, but it gives Black some additional options. However, I don't think this is as obvious either, and in general, it is also playable (although not as interesting as our main line starting with 7.Bg5). What annoys me the most here is the move} Na5 {But here I found an original set up:} (8... g5 9. Bg3 {Transposes to our main line.}) 9. Qe2 Nxc4 10. dxc4 $5 $13 {And in return for the bishop pair, White has decent control over the center, and the pin on h4-d8 would probably force Black to play g5 sooner or later, weakening his position a bit. I think this position is totally fine and can also be a try for the White player.}) 8... g5 {And now let me show for you the critical line:} 9. Bg3 $5 {This option is more practical, but as I explained earlier, I don't think this line is very practical because of the possibility of 9.Nxg5 (which can be scary for someone seeing this position for the first time). However, objectively, it doesn't work for subtle tactical reasons. That's why I suggest trying this more neutral move against this move order to save energy for our main line with g5 directly.} (9. Nxg5 Nxd5 10. Qh5 $1 Qf6 {All these moves are forced. Black, however, should see in advance a spectacular resource.} 11. Nh7 $5 Qg6 (11... Rxh7 $3 12. Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Qh4 Ke7 (13... Ng4 {looks natural but after} 14. Rf1 {the knight is running out of squares. After the forced} Ne7 15. h3 Ng6 16. Qg3 Nf6 17. O-O-O $132 {the position is totally unclear.}) 14. h3 Be6 (14... Rg7 15. g4) 15. Bxe6 fxe6 16. O-O-O {Here, the computer indicates that after ...Rg8, provoking g2-g4, Black is better. Once again, I would like to ask you a question: does it look reasonable to calculate such a variation on move 7? I don't think so. However, I will not make it our main line because it does not work well objectively. Also, considering that this move order does not seem natural and practical at all, it makes sense to try to have an easier way to deal with it and save energy for our work in the main line (g5 directly).}) 12. exd5 Qxh5 (12... Rxh7 13. Qxg6 fxg6 14. dxc6 bxc6 $11) 13. Nf6+) 9... Nxd5 10. Bxd5 Bg4 {It's important to know how to meet this thematic move.} (10... Ne7 11. Bb3 Ng6 {This is also very normal. Nevertheless, after} 12. h4 g4 ({Black can also play} 12... Bg4 13. hxg5 hxg5 14. Rxh8+ Nxh8 15. Qd2 Bxf3 16. gxf3 Qf6 17. c3 Ng6 18. O-O-O {Objectively speaking, Black is doing fine but White has practical chances.}) {White has the fantastic} 13. d4 $3 Ba7 14. h5 Nf4 15. dxe5 {Very precise play by White!} Nxg2+ (15... gxf3 16. Bxf4 fxg2 17. Rg1 $36) 16. Kf1 gxf3 17. Qxf3 $16) 11. c3 Qf6 12. Bxc6+ (12. b4 Ba7 13. h3 Bh5 (13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxf3 15. gxf3 {I am not a fan of this position. It is just equal, but I don't think that White is trying anything here, because of the extremely bad bishop.})) 12... bxc6 13. Qa4 O-O 14. Nd2 $132 {In this position, both sides have their assets: Black has the bishop pair and good control of the center. White has mainly managed to spoil Black's structure, and most importantly, Black's king is permanently not safe. The computer assesses this as 0.00 as always, but I am very happy to have managed to get such a complicated and original position out of the opening. In general, as this move order is highly unlikely, I don't think we should analyze this more deeply, because the chances of getting this particular line are not very high. I just want to give an illustrative line that shows that White has some potential even against very natural moves by Black.} Bd7 {Taking into account that c6-pawn is hanging, this looks like a normal reaction. But after} 15. h4 g4 16. O-O $14 {I prefer White. The king will find a very nice and safe square on h2, and we can slowly prepare a break in the centre.}) 8. a4 $1 {An important move. The idea is to answer ...Na5 with Ba2.} d6 {And now a VERY subtle move by White -} 9. h3 $3 {This move looks normal, but in reality, it is just beautiful! What's the idea behind it? You are creating an escape square for your h4-bishop. So you want to go for Bg3, and if Nh5, your bishop has an escape square on h2. Why is this important? Because you have a space advantage, and you don't want to exchange unnecessary pieces, such as the h4-bishop. You should not trade it so easily. But this raises a question: What if Black goes for 9...Nh5 now? And here comes our main tactical point.} O-O (9... Nh5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nd5 Qd8 12. Nxe5 $1 {This is our tactical point, and for this reason, Black can´t go for Nh5.}) 10. Bg3 $1 {Our idea is to castle, and if Black keeps waiting, we can slowly prepare the d4 break with Re1. The only way to free Black's position for now is the move Be6.} Be6 {And now I would like to suggest a very tipical aproach -} (10... Re8 11. O-O Bf8 {Black wants to play ...Be6 without damaging his pawn structure.} 12. a5 Be6 13. Bxe6 Rxe6 14. Re1 Qd7 15. Nd5 $14 {Black is in a very passive position. White has an obvious advantage.}) 11. Bxe6 fxe6 {And don´t wait even a minute, go for} 12. Ne2 $1 {You may ask, "Why move this knight?" The reason is very simple. After the structure changes due to the fxe6 capture, the knight is no longer well-placed on c3 as the e6 pawn controls it. Therefore, we move our knight to e2 and prepare the advance c2-c3.} Nh5 13. c3 {We shoud not lose time anymore. Just focus on the necessary moves: c3, and 0-0.} Nxg3 {Now comes a very parodical move, but one that i like very much.} 14. fxg3 $1 {This move may not seem easy at first, but it is very important! The g3-pawn controls some very important squares now, and Black is left with the "wrong" knight. Additionally, the bishop on e7 is not active and with no pawns on f2, there's nothing to attack on the f-file. In my opinion, White has a more comfortable position here. Here's an illustrative line:} d5 15. O-O $1 dxe4 16. dxe4 Qxd1 17. Rfxd1 Bc5+ 18. Kf1 Rad8 19. b4 $14 {Due to his queenside space advantage, White is more confortable. Pay attention to how miserable is the c6-knight!} *

