{[%evp 0,37,19,36,28,10,18,18,18,18,7,18,20,8,26,6,13,13,-15,-29,-29,-29,-7,-25,-23,-32,-1,-26,-26,-33,10,18,18,-15,26,17,17,28,13,13]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 $5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 $5 g5 {This is a totally critical way to question White's concept, and without a doubt, the way to go. But before entering into more tense positions, we also have to answer another question: How to handle White's position if Black goes for the more solid Be7 setup now? Let's analyze it together} 8. Bg3 d6 {First, let's try to understand why this position is considered dubious. White's bishop on g3 looks completely out of play. There is a similar line in the Italian, where the knight on c3 is on d2, and White's c2 pawn is on c3. This position (with the knight on d2) is considered to be totally playable for White. However, the exact position that we have on the board looks like a much worse version, because the knight on c3 looks completely misplaced and restricts the c2 pawn from helping White to fight for the center with c3-d4. But when I looked at this position for the first time, I immediately understood that things can't be that simple. I agree that the knight on c3 is not ideally placed, but it has some function on c3, and this pawn on g5 always has some drawbacks (it exposes Black's position a bit). At first, the computer is not happy with White's position (due to the problems we already mentioned), but after analyzing these issues more deeply, I finally managed to make it work.} 9. Nd2 {This is an important move to prevent Bg4. However, I would also like to mention that Bg4 is not exactly a deadly threat as one might think (since the times of Capablanca, players have been terribly afraid of such structures, and it makes sense as Capablanca won a very beautiful game in this structure). But in this specific situation, White would have some interesting resources that I would like to show.} (9. a3 $5 Bg4 {And now we have to be VERY cautious. Black has a LETHAL threat right now: Just imagine that white plays a random move like Ba2, after Nd4, we are really in BIG trouble. But here we have a concrete solution:} (9... Ba7 {Nd2 sort of transposes to our lines. So Bg4 is the independent try.}) 10. h3 Bh5 11. h4 {And it is not entirely easy to maintain the pin without losing some material. One trick that Black has to be cautious of is} Nd4 {Looks normal, but almost loses by force.} (11... Qe7 {This is the critical move, maintaining the tension. Here, White looks to be in a very risky situation because of the pin, and the bishop on g3 is at risk of getting out of play. But once again, I have found a resource.} 12. Bd5 $1 {And here, Black should play} O-O-O 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Qe2 {This position still looks tense to me. At the end of the day, the king on c8 is not exactly safe. But Black has some advantages as well, like the bishops, and the bishop on g3 being in a strange position. In general, I find this position playable, and Black has to make some not-so-easy decisions to reach it.}) 12. hxg5 hxg5 {This is the normal reaction, trying to mantain the pin, but here White has an amazing resource.} 13. Nxd4 $3 Bxd1 (13... exd4 14. Nd5 {Black can just resign, The queen on d1 is on prise, but after Rxh8+ Black loses a lot of material.}) 14. Rxh8+ $18) 9... Be6 {Here we are following the analysis of Grandmaster Michael Roiz in his Modern Chess database on the Italian. I have a lot of respect for Mr. Roiz, so I decided to focus our analysis on his suggestions and understand where we can improve with White. And in my opinion, in this particular case, this is a feasible task.} (9... Na5 $5 {One question that we should definitely answer here is: Why can't Black just (like a normal player) try to take the bishop on c4? But in this specific position, it loses some time, which White can use to create play on the kingside.} 10. h4 $1 Nxc4 11. Nxc4 g4 $6 (11... Rg8 12. hxg5 hxg5 13. Qd2 {White is having more fun here. We can keep playing very natural moves such as f2-f3 followed by Bf2 and 0-0-0. Even though Black is very solid, White's play is easier.}) 12. h5 $1 $14 {White is already planning to follow with the annoying Bh4. Remember this typical way of activating the bishop.}) 10. h4 g4 11. h5 {White is threatening to play Bh4.} Qd7 12. a3 {With this move, we put the ball in Black's court, and it turns out that the position is not so simple.} b5 (12... O-O-O 13. Bh4 {Is the problem.}) 13. Ba2 Bxa2 14. Nxa2 {This is our improvement over Roiz's analysis. The reason behind taking with the knight instead of the rook is that, firstly, White still has the option to castle long in certain scenarios. Additionally, this specific configuration also gives White some new options. The main reason why I started to look in this direction was the fact that with these pawns on g4 and b5, Black's king has no safe squares anymore. It would not be logical if White's position did not have any resources in such a situation.} (14. Rxa2 Rg8 15. Nf1 (15. Nb3 Bb6 16. Qd2 Rg5 {This is one of the lines where we can see that White´s rook would be better on a1. Check the lines below.}) 15... d5 {And according to Roiz, Black is better.I think it makes sense since I see no useful moves for White here.}) 14... Rg8 {Trying to use the idea of Roiz does not work here. But we will make it the main line because it makes sense to try to use the author's idea. After that, we will analyze different options for Black.} (14... O-O {This also looks normal for me. A possible continuation would be} 15. Nc3 Kh7 16. Nf1 $5 {This is not the only way to continue in this position, but it looks natural to me. Here, the computer suggests that only one move by Black is adequate, and that is Qe6. It looks like a normal move, of course, but Black has to correctly evaluate the consequences of the following crazy line:} Qe6 (16... Rae8 17. Ne3 $14) 17. Bh4 {This is the more forcing option. Do not try to memorize the following lines, I just analyse them for the sake of curiosity.} (17. Ne3 $5 {Is totally playable.}) 17... Nxh5 18. Bg5 hxg5 19. Rxh5+ Kg6 20. Ng3 Rh8 21. Rxh8 Rxh8 22. Nd5 Rh2 23. Kf1 Nd4 {I think this resource is not that difficult for a very strong player to find if they arrive in this position. But to see this resource many moves ago is not easy!} 24. c3 Nf3 {This is the point. Computer starts finding some crazy perpetuals from here.} 25. b4 Ba7 26. d4 exd4 27. gxf3 dxc3 28. Ra2 $1 c6 29. Nxc3 Qc4+ 30. Kg1 Rxf2 31. Rxf2 Qxc3 32. Qxd6+ f6 33. Kg2 Bxf2 34. Kxf2 Qxf3+ 35. Kg1 Qe3+ 36. Kg2 Qf3+ {And it is a draw.}) (14... Qe6 {According to the computer, this is the best move.} 15. Nc3 O-O-O {I don't know about you, but when I start to analyze this position, the idea of playing Qe6 and castling queenside doesn't even cross my mind. I don't think it's easy to find. But more than that, even if Black finds this idea, the position is still okay. Let's continue our analysis.} 16. Bh4 Rdg8 17. g3 Nxh5 {This is the critical position. Now, my suggestion is} 18. Nd5 f5 19. b4 $1 Bb6 20. a4 $36 {I will stop my analysis here. According to the computer, this position is just equal, but only Kb7 holds. All other moves for Black result in a lost position. However, I think we are getting too far into the variation. Bh4 is already a kind of new move, and we are already on move 20. To arrive at this position, Black already had to find very difficult moves, and their life is still not easy.} fxe4 {After this natural move, for example, Black is lost.} (20... Kb7 {This is the only move to keep Black in the game, but the position is totally insane, and I don't think it's realistic to imagine Black arriving here. Even if it were to happen, it is just a complicated position with chances for both sides. For extremely curious readers, I suggest continuing to analyze it. The positions are incredibly complex, and, as always, it ends up being equal.}) 21. dxe4 $18 Kb7 22. c3 {White is ready to castle short. He has a powerful attack in this position.}) 15. Nb3 Bb6 16. Qd2 Rg5 {We are basically trying to do the same thing as recommended in Roiz´s database. But here, with our rook still on a1, the position is different. After:} 17. Nc3 O-O-O 18. Bh4 Rxh5 {White can play} 19. O-O-O $1 $16 {This is the point. White is close to winning here.} *

