{[%evp 0,31,19,11,9,9,15,18,18,12,12,8,12,12,10,13,28,29,33,33,24,21,18,22,17,24,20,20,12,0,20,23,37,40]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 h6 {This is the last attempt. As I explained in the example in the Model section, the idea behind this move is basically the same as in the a6-line: waiting to play d6 (to avoid Na4) but also avoiding the Bg5 line by not going for a6. However, as I explained there, in this h6-line, Black is committed to moving both flank pawns (a and h), which takes some time. This extra time can be used by White to go for the Be3 structures in a better circumstance. For this reason, I recommend the Be3 setup against h6+a6 because here Black loses more time in the process.} ({After} 5... O-O 6. O-O h6 {we will transpose to the main line.}) 6. O-O (6. h3 {It is entirely possible to start with this move and only then go for 0-0. This move order, however, provides White with an additional option against} O-O {Here, we can play} 7. g4 $5 {with serious attacking chances.}) 6... O-O ({In case of} 6... a6 {we should play} 7. Be3 {Play Be3 only after Black has committed to both ...h7-h6 and ...a7-a6.}) 7. h3 {Very important waiting move. A rule of thumb that I would like to suggest here is the following: Do not go for Be3 if the pawn is still on a7.} ({If you try the immediate} 7. Be3 {Black has at his disposal the following move} Bb6 $1 {Had the black pawn been on a6, Black wouldn't have had this possibility.}) 7... a6 (7... d6 8. Na4 {just transposes to Line 1 of the theoritical coverage. Our conclusion is that White is slightly better here.}) 8. Be3 Bxe3 (8... d6 $5 {This move is also interesting. It's not a very popular concept, but at the highest level, it's gaining some popularity. On the one hand, Black is sacrificing the flexibility of his pawn structure, but on the other hand, he's trying to get a super-solid position in which he'll never have to worry about the c3-d4 break. Overall, it looks like a way to get a very solid but slightly passive position. Because, of course, Black no longer has any breaks available (he loses the d6-d5 break, which is very important) and should focus on playing with his pieces. Black is solid enough to be fine here, but I'm not sure if I would be happy playing Black in this position, because it feels like he's often playing for only two results (loss or draw). And if you find my arguments too abstract, we also have some practical evidence to confirm or refute our impressions: apart from a single win by Guijarro, all other high-level games have resulted in a win or a draw for White up to the present moment (March 2023).} 9. Bxc5 dxc5 10. a4 {White's idea here is to consolidate his position and slowly improve the pieces. Let's follow a high-level game to understand where to place our pieces in such a structure.} Re8 11. Re1 Be6 12. Nd2 {This knight will help us in the fight for the control of the light squares in Black's camp.} b6 13. Bxe6 Rxe6 14. Nc4 Qd7 15. Rf1 Rb8 16. Ne3 {White's plan here is to slowly consolidate the position and improve his pieces, with the eventual goal of playing f4. The first step is to maximize the potential of the pieces by playing Qd2, b3, Rae1, and Kh2. Only then should we consider playing f4. This break is crucial and should not be played superficially. It is important to use it at the most opportune moment, which is usually after having improved one's position as much as possible. Black, understanding that waiting would lead to a passive position, decides to activate his pieces with:} b5 {And here after:} 17. axb5 axb5 18. Ncd5 {White is clearly pressing in Abudsattorov, N - So, W (Jul 2022).}) 9. fxe3 {I remember being recommended such positions in my childhood! Of course, back then my teacher suggested that White would give mate on the kingside! However, strong players understand that it is not easy to give mate only with the f-file. For this reason, this kind of idea was always ignored by theory. White's play looks too obvious to be good. But now, with the help of computers, we start to see that we can combine some very subtle maneuvering moves with action on both flanks and keep the tension in the game. One thing that adds to White's case here is that Black's knight on c6 is very bad, and it takes some time to organize this piece to a better square. White will use this time to generate some play.} d6 10. a4 Be6 {And here, White has two options to maintain the tension between these bishops: Nd2 and b3. I would like to suggest that you keep both options in your arsenal, but I would give preference to Nd2. It looks more testing and is the preference of Italian expert Alekseenko.} 11. Nd2 $5 (11. b3 $5 {This move is also very interesting. The idea is basically the same as in the Nd2 variation: to keep the tension between the bishops in a very original way. I prefer Nd2 because it keeps even more tension, but I think you can vary between Nd2 and b3 without any problems.} d5 12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Qd2 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 e4 (14... Bxc4 15. Qxc4 Qd6 16. Nd2) 15. dxe4 Bxc4 16. Qxc4 (16. bxc4 Qe7) 16... Qe7 17. Nd4 {White's position is easier to handle.}) (11. Bxe6 $5 {I just want to mention that I think this kind of position is not totally without life.} fxe6 {Because after that, of course, Black is objectively okay, but the knight on c6 is still not great, and White is a few tempi ahead. One plan is to go for Ne2-g3, followed by c3. Once again, White has no advantage here, but such positions have more life than one tends to think. One very recent example of such structures was Donchenko vs. Latasa (2023), where White won a very fine game. But still, we have two interesting options at our disposal (b3, Nd2), and I think we can stick with them (with Nd2 being our main choice).}) 11... Bxc4 12. Nxc4 d5 {Of course, Black has many options, but the verdict remains the same: there's no way for Black to kill the game, and the position remains playable. The advance ...d6-d5 is the only way I can see to try to simplify matters, and for this reason, I decided to make it the main line. One more reason that adds to this is that we have two games by GM Alekseenko, a big expert of this line. But of course, we should address how White can proceed if Black just keeps playing normal moves.} (12... Qd7 {This one looks normal, but allows a very typical sacrifice -} 13. Rxf6 $1 gxf6 14. Nd5 $18 {White is already winning.}) (12... Qe7 {And this is for sure a more solid option, but White has another thematic idea at his disposal -} 13. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 14. exd5 Nb8 {And now, a VERY POWERFULL maneuvre:} 15. e4 $3 $16 {followed by Ne3-f5, with a huge advantage for White.}) (12... Nb4 {After looking at all of this, it becomes clear why Nb4 is the more solid option. But here, I like White's perspective. I would like to show you some interesting ideas that White has in such scenarios.} 13. Rf2 {Besides overprotecting the c2-pawn, White is planning to double the rook on the f-file.} b6 14. Qe2 Qe7 15. Raf1 Nh7 {Black needs to prevent the dangerous exchange sacrifice on f6. Now, however, White can increase the pressure with} 16. Nd2 $1 {The knight is heading for the kingside.} Nxc2 $2 {This move is just losing on the spot.} ({Better would have been} 16... Rae8 17. Nf3 Kh8 18. g4 $14 {when White's play is obviously easier.}) 17. Nd5 Qd8 18. Nc4 $18 {The c2-knight is trapped. Black can already resign.}) 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. e4 $1 Nxc3 15. bxc3 b5 16. Ne3 $14 {Alekseenko had two games in this position and managed to win both. White is slightly better here. Black's knight on c6 is bad, and he is suffering from a lack of space.} *

