{[%evp 0,25,79,48,56,39,5,13,17,17,14,19,14,14,29,16,27,-29,12,-13,14,5,19,27,14,20,42,22]} 1. e4 {But now, dear reader, I would like to offer you a few bonus chapters. In these chapters, I will suggest alternative lines to our main repertoire, because, as explained in our introduction, variety is key in Italian, and for this reason, it is important to be able to generate more and different ideas. In this section, we will analyze one more interesting attempt against the h6 move order.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 h6 6. h3 {As explained in our theoretical coverage, 0-0 is our main option. However, for this line, I want to analyze one independent attempt.} a6 {And now, instead of our main and more normal option (Be3) I would like to suggest something different:} (6... O-O {One important point about this move order, is that the very natural 0-0 is already a very dubious decision. Because after} 7. g4 {Black already has practical problems. After a normal move like} a6 (7... b5 {This counterintuitive move is the suggestion of the computer. Let's keep examining the position.} 8. Bb3 {I don't want to accept the pawn and misplace my bishop.} a5 9. g5 a4 10. gxf6 {Black will have to understand that he is forced to give the piece -} Qxf6 ({After} 10... axb3 11. fxg7 $18 {White is winning.}) 11. Bd5 {And now, the key idea:} Nd4 $3 12. Bxa8 Nxf3+ 13. Kf1 c6 {The computer is stating that Black is holding here without his rook. I don't think this sequence is easy to find over the board. Even if it is the case, White is not running serious risks here, and more than that, it is totally possible to go for Bxb5 on move 8. I just gave this as our main line because I found this whole sequence very difficult.}) 8. g5 {Believe me: Black is already lost! White's attack is decisive. In just eight moves, this is what happens when Black does not understand such positions.} hxg5 9. Bxg5 Be7 10. Rg1 d6 11. Bh6 Nh5 12. Ng5 $18) 7. a4 {As you know by now, a useful normal move is to go for Be3 after d6, but we have something different in mind:} d6 8. Ne2 $5 {This is my second recommendation. I think this move is totally playable and leads to normal Italian positions. The reason why I don't put this as our main line is that the lines here are very close to the normal Italian (with d3 and c3), and I tried to maintain this repertoire more in the 5.Nc3 spirit. But as I explained, it is always great to have more options. The idea of this move is to put the knight on g3 more quickly. Generally, this knight arrives on g3 via Nd2-Re1-Nf1-Ng3. That is four moves. This Ne2-g3 idea consumes one tempo less. I think Black has basically three options here. The first is to keep playing normally, in my opinion, this is the worst of the options. The second one is to go for the Be6 structure. The last and most critical option is the d5 plan (makes a lot of sense now that the "c3" knight abandoned the d5 square).} Ne7 (8... O-O 9. O-O d5 {This is the critical try.} (9... Ne7 {transposes to the lines we have already seen. I think here White is just slightly better for the reasons already mentioned.}) (9... Be6 {This is totally normal. And this will lead to an important structure for Italian players, Lets check it together:} 10. Bxe6 fxe6 11. c3 {I want to discuss this position with you. This kind of structure was considered a dream for Black for many years. Black has, on paper, huge counterplay along the 'f' file, and White has nothing. But things have changed! These days, players are very much afraid of these doubled 'e' pawns for the reasons we already studied in our course: these pawns are not very mobile, and this f-file pressure is not too hard to deal with. The rule of thumb in this position is that if White is able to get b2-b4 in these structures, he is better! Because then White can combine queenside play with the constant threat to go for d3-d4. But here, we are not exactly in time.} a5 $1 {Stopping the progress of White on the queenside is very important. But I still think that White's position is very much playable after} 12. Be3 $5 Bxe3 13. fxe3 Ne7 14. Qb3 Qd7 15. Ng3 Ng6 16. d4 {And I don't want to claim an advantage for White here, but I think this position is totally playable. You can follow with Nd2-c4 and, in certain cases, also double the rooks on the f-file. This Qb3 is very annoying for Black, and he has just no active counterplay. Having said that, Black is solid enough to be okay here, but still, I think it makes sense to go for this.}) 10. exd5 Nxd5 {Black is claiming that after this c3 knight abandons control over d5, he can occupy the center. I find this position totally playable, and here we have almost no games! Let's check how the game can proceed from here.} 11. c3 Re8 12. Ng3 {Normal moves. We are trying to get Re1 + Bd2 and start gaining space on the queenside with b4.} Be6 {We are still following two games here. Both very high-level ones. Eljanov vs Dominguez, and Ponkratov vs Erigaisi.} 13. Qc2 Nf6 {Here, instead of taking on e6, I suggest} 14. Re1 $5 Bf8 (14... Bxc4 15. dxc4 a5 {Black should stop the advance b2-b4.} 16. Be3 Bxe3 17. Rxe3 {[%cal Ga1e1] With Re1 coming, this position looks playable.}) 15. Bxe6 (15. b4 {will be answered with} e4 16. Nxe4 Bxc4 17. dxc4 Nxe4 18. Rxe4 Rxe4 19. Qxe4 Qd1+ 20. Qe1 Qxe1+ 21. Nxe1 a5 {and thanks to this exact move, Black equalizes.}) 15... Rxe6 16. b4 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ga1d1] With Be3 and Rad1 coming, I find this position absolutely playable for White thanks to his space advantage on the queenside. Of course, Black is fine, but he had to work to arrive here.}) 9. Ng3 Ng6 10. O-O O-O {I don't like this approach by Black. This is very close to some normal Italians. The rule here is that if Black is able to play c6-d5 in such positions in good conditions, he will be fine. And if White is able to execute c3-d4, his position will be better. I think here we are in time!} 11. c3 c6 12. d4 Ba7 13. Bd3 $14 {We are better. We are controlling the center, and you can keep playing with Re1-Be3. I seriously dislike Black´s position.} *

