{[%evp 0,29,19,31,34,34,38,28,23,23,3,15,15,11,-2,6,1,6,6,7,9,15,9,-3,24,28,31,27,41,32,13,17]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. d3 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {And against the a6 move order (against d6 directly, I don't think we need more than the Na4 option; Black is just suffering there), but against both a6 and h6, I also would like to suggest the more normal approach, which is very close to the lines we already analyzed in the h6 theoretical part.} 6. a4 (6. Bg5 {Is our main move.}) 6... d6 7. Be3 Bxe3 8. fxe3 {This line is very close to the position we analyzed in the h6 section, but here Black has not lost a tempo on ...h7-h6. This helps Black's case in my opinion. On the other hand, we also do not lose the tempo with h3. But in general, I find the inclusion of h3-h6 to be slightly preferable for White, as h3 cuts off the g4-square for Black's pieces, and I don't see what the h6 pawn is doing on h6. But all in all, this position remains totally playable. Let's keep following a very recent example:} O-O 9. O-O Be6 10. Nd2 {Once again, the same motif!} Nb4 {This was tried in the recent game Abdusattorov vs Nakamura. Now, instead of a4-a5, White could have played} 11. h3 $146 {and only after} c6 {we can fix the structure with} 12. a5 Rb8 (12... d5 13. Bb3 $14) 13. Rf2 h6 14. Ra4 c5 15. Bb3 $14 {All in all, I find this line not too ambitious, but it is definitely playable for White and very close in spirit to our main repertoire.} *

